To determine whether the combined treatment can increase the intracellular reactive oxygen species (ROS), cells exposed sequentially to X-rays at 0.5, 2.5 or 5Gy, and 1Hz-PRF US were immediately incubated with 3′-(p-Aminophenyl) fluorescein (APF; Invitrogen) for 15min at 20°C under gentle shaking. Afterwards, fluorescence was measured flow cytometrically (APF excitation/emission: 490/515nm). APF is a cell permeable compound that exhibits slight basal fluorescence. Its fluorescence is strongly enhanced upon reaction with ROS. The probe possesses high activity towards hydroxyl (OH) radicals as well as hypochlorite (OCl−) and peroxynitrite (ONOO−) radicals, but less active towards other ROS, e.g., superoxide anion (O2
                        −
                        ) and peroxides [17,18].

The cell cycle is the most important determinant in cell sensitivity to X-irradiation. X-rays primarily work through the induction of DNA lesions, and the cell cycle usually halts in response to allow for DNA integrity check and repair. Cells are likely to undergo arrest in G1 and G2M phases after X-irradiation. However, departures from this typical response are cited in other studies [31]. Here, the cell cycle changes have been determined 24h after different treatments (Tables 1 and 2

                     ). Both of the leukemic cell lines showed a significant increase in G2M fraction only whereas G1 phase dropped significantly (Fig. 5
                     ). This signifies that the inhibition of replicative DNA synthesis in cells has priority over halting the cell cycle in non-replicative phases (G1 cells) [32,33]. Although this mechanism is critical to avoid cellular transformation, it seems to be also conserved in cancer cells, even those with non-functional p53 (U937 cells). Significant changes in cell cycle were observed at lower doses with radiation-sensitive Molt-4 cells, whereas the extent of change was higher in U937 cells. The effect on G1 and G2M peaks plateaued at 2.5Gy for both cell lines indicating that a dose of 5Gy comes on a high dose–effect scale compared to 0.5 and 2.5Gy doses. A significant increase in subG1 (supposedly apoptotic cells) was observed in Molt-4 cells at all X-ray doses and at 5Gy only in U937 cells.
